******
[6] Nebraska (Knox County): commercial poultry
Date: Thu 28 Apr 2022
Source: The Beatrice Daily Sun [edited]
https://beatricedailysun.com/news/state-and-regional/large-bird-flu-outbreak-reported-at-knox-county-farm/article_e2f11a6a-03c2-5186-867f-60df87144a83.html


Another large case of bird flu has been confirmed at a farm in Nebraska, state and federal agriculture officials said Wednesday [27 Apr 2022].

The highly-contagious avian influenza was found on a farm in Knox County in northeast Nebraska along the South Dakota border.

It is the 7th confirmed case of the disease in the state this year [2022], the Nebraska Department of Agriculture said in a news release.

More than 2.1 million laying hens will be euthanized, agriculture officials said. The farm will also be quarantined and a 6.2-mile [10 km] control zone will be established.

The department also announced an order prohibiting any type of birds from events such as fairs, expositions, swap meets, exotic sales and live bird auctions has been extended to [15 May 2022]. It was scheduled to expire on Saturday [30 Apr 2022].

--
Communicated by:
ProMED from HealthMap Alerts

[As one looks through the postings of the rampage of Avian Influenza, it becomes abundantly clear this virus is sweeping through the country a grim reaper. The virus is merciless to both domestic birds and some species of wild birds in the USA and Canada.

Destroyed bird counts are increasingly going up. This means live bird counts are going down, affecting eggs and meat birds and decreasing wildlife. As dead bird counts mount, the cost is rising in the grocery stores, and in the cost of replacement birds.

It is critical to protect your birds. Zoos and aviaries should have birds protected from wild birds and from the public. Biosecurity of any facility is paramount to trying to protect the birds. - Mod.TG

